Issues involved in the selection of a textbook are discussed. Included are the diversity of marriage and family course offerings, the difficulties in locating appropriate materials, and criteria for text selection. Fourteen university texts published in 1987 and 1988 are reviewed according to: (a) scope of course/text, (b) organizational theme, (c) readability, (d) sensitivity to cultural issues, (e) topics covered, and (f) supplementary materials available. Texts that cover aspects of marriage and family in less breadth but with greater depth are called for. A regularly published listing of available materials would also be helpful to instructors.
